The English translation of "Eine neue Wissenschaft" is "A new science."
This summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers gathered to ponder the necessity of a new science that could be as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists assume that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
Considering the great challenges, it is believed that there is little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: Firstly, the great unsolved mysteries of science (such as unifying gravity and electricity in a theory), which require enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World to explore. Secondly, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and thirdly, problems whose solutions must be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Moreover, it is generally believed that the only difficult part of the work would be to use already known natural laws with the help of new technologies for the benefit of humanity.
Who could disagree with that?
The models of today do work, after all.
However, an increasing group of scientists point out phenomena that are not so easily explained by today's theories.
These problems, while becoming more frequent, are also cleverly avoided because the science with which to explain these problems simply does not exist.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
The knowledge in the individual scientific disciplines is fairly well secured.
At least the part of physics that we normal people encounter is well-researched.
The chemistry and biochemistry are also based on solid foundations – while there are still a few things in our body that we do not yet understand, it is reasonable to assume that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
Additionally, there are the new social sciences that focus on people and societies.
In each of these areas—physics, biochemistry, and social sciences—the theories are well-established and are largely uncontested.
Every discipline has its own language and mechanisms.
In the rarest cases is a scientist an expert in more than one field because these worlds and languages are just that different.
This means that we cannot find an answer to complex questions that require the involvement of several disciplines.
For example, think of the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interaction occurs on the basis of physics. The information conveyed during this process is transmitted due to the laws of electricity.
Furthermore, there is a system of specialized cells that communicate with each other through the exchange of chemical substances and also transmit information.
The interaction between two brains adds a new level: Here, information is exchanged through language, symbols, and ideas.
At every level, it involves the exchange of information, and there are appropriate theories that explain the processes at each level.
However, information is also exchanged between the individual levels, but there is no science that could even begin to explain this flow of information.
To compensate for this deficiency, some scientists have tried to redefine the instrumentation for explaining processes within one level, and then apply it to another level.
These experiments then lead to something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanation patterns works well, but the fundamental problem is not addressed: What is the nature of the information exchanged between individual levels, and how is it transmitted?
Now almost all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this embarrassing lack of knowledge about how the system as a whole functions.
The group of interdisciplinary scientists who gathered in Paris has loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science."
The researchers come from various countries and disciplines and have been working together on a decentralized basis for eight years.
In addition to scientists from the relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, linguists, and philosophers are also beginning to participate in the discourse.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy," where the scientific foundations are adapted and supplemented to fit another level.
Others, on the other hand, believe that a completely new approach is required.
In your opinion, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents, and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches emerge from scientists who currently do not have access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Completely free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Almost all activities that take place under the banner of "science" have developed an institutional character, similar to their counterparts in the world of business.
It is believed that developing countries should build similar resources as industrial countries. However, this could stifle creative thinking nonetheless.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas originate from laboratories and research centers that are not associated with the larger institutions.
The most carefully devised approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came from the Soviet Union for twenty years, where computer capacities were scarce at every turn.
The most genius and literally world-shaking insights in the field of physics over the last decades did not come where expected from known innovation hubs, but from Budapest.
There is a tradition of architecture in Iran that has provided cognitive scientists with important insights.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of second-generation artificial intelligence (the so-called "autonomous agents") originate today from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements entered history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, it changed the identity of space and time. The FIS Conference in July was the unexpected start of an attempt to redefine the universe in this manner.
Those gaps were identified for which explanations must be found.
More scientists from innovative regions will be included in this group to identify those problems that could be solved once this new science is developed, or discovered, if you will.
